.TH SNAPSTATS 1 "2026-03-08" "snapstats" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
snapstats \- SnapRAID content file scrub age statistics
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B snapstats
[\fIOPTIONS\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B snapstats
parses a SnapRAID content file and reports scrub age statistics per file,
per disk, and across the array. It does not read from or write to any data
disk — all information is extracted from the content file alone.
.PP
The content file reflects the state of the array as of the last successful
.B snapraid sync
run. Files added or deleted since then are not visible to snapstats.
.PP
On first run, parsed statistics are cached in
.IR /var/cache/snapstats/snapstats.cache .
Subsequent runs within 2 hours reuse the cache if the content file has not
changed (checked via mtime and size). This reduces a typical runtime of
~3 seconds to under 0.3 seconds.
.SH OPTIONS
.SS "Output control"
.TP
.B \-\-disk
Show a per-disk scrub age breakdown below the main chart.
.TP
.BI \-\-top \ N
Show the
.I N
oldest files by scrub age (default 20 if flag is given without a number).
Files with zero size are excluded.
.TP
.B \-\-all
Equivalent to
.B \-\-disk \-\-top\ 20 .
.TP
.B \-\-json
Output a JSON summary to stdout instead of the visual report.
Implies
.BR \-\-no\-color .
See
.B JSON OUTPUT
below.
.TP
.B \-q ", " \-\-quiet
Suppress all output. Useful in cron jobs where only the exit code matters.
Mutually exclusive with
.BR \-\-verbose .
.TP
.B \-v ", " \-\-verbose
Show parse and cache progress. Mutually exclusive with
.BR \-\-quiet .
.TP
.B \-\-no\-color
Disable ANSI color output. Also honoured via the
.B NO_COLOR
environment variable.
.SS "Threshold and alerting"
.TP
.BI \-\-max\-age \ DAYS
Exit with code
.B 2
if the oldest scrubbed file exceeds
.I DAYS
days. Must be at least 1.
Also collapses the age chart so that rows beyond
.I DAYS
are merged into a single
.RI \fIDays\fR+
bucket (shown in red).
.SS "Content file location"
.TP
.BI \-\-content \ PATH
Use
.I PATH
as the content file instead of reading the location from snapraid.conf.
.TP
.BI \-\-conf \ PATH
Use
.I PATH
as the snapraid.conf file.
Default:
.IR /etc/snapraid.conf .
.SS "Cache control"
.TP
.B \-\-no\-cache
Ignore any existing cache and force a full re-parse. The new results are
written back to the cache.
.TP
.B \-\-use\-cache
Use the cache even if it is older than the 2-hour TTL. The content file
signature is still verified — if the content file has changed the cache is
discarded and a full re-parse is performed regardless.
Mutually exclusive with
.BR \-\-no\-cache .
.SH "CHART LAYOUT"
The main output is an 80-column scrub age chart. Each row represents a
distinct scrub age in days. Rows with zero files are hidden, except for the
.I 60+
(or
.IR N+ )
and
.I not scrubbed
rows which always appear.
.PP
Bar width scales proportionally to file count. The percentage shown is
the fraction of total tracked files in that age bucket.
.PP
Zero-byte files have no data blocks and are excluded from scrub tracking.
They are counted separately and shown in the footer as
.IR (+N\ empty) .
.SS "Color codes"
.TS
l l.
\fBGreen (bright)\fR	today / \(<=7 days
\fBGreen\fR	8\(en14 days
\fBYellow\fR	15\(en30 days
\fBRed\fR	31+ days, or \fIN+\fR bucket when \fB\-\-max\-age\fR is set
\fBDark gray\fR	never scrubbed
.TE
.SH "JSON OUTPUT"
When
.B \-\-json
is used, a single JSON object is printed to stdout. Fields:
.TP
.B generated
ISO 8601 UTC timestamp of the run.
.TP
.B total_files
Total number of files tracked in the content file.
.TP
.B total_size
Total size in bytes.
.TP
.B unscrubbed_files
Number of non-zero-byte files with no scrub record.
.TP
.B unscrubbed_size
Total size in bytes of unscrubbed files.
.TP
.B oldest_scrub_days
Age in days of the oldest scrubbed block across all files.
.TP
.B oldest_scrub_file
Path of the file containing that oldest block.
.TP
.B per_disk
Object keyed by disk name. Each entry has
.BR files ,
.BR size ,
and
.B oldest_scrub_days
fields.
.TP
.B empty_disks
Array of disk names present in the content file but containing no files.
.TP
.B max_age_threshold
Only present when
.B \-\-max\-age
is used. The threshold value supplied.
.TP
.B max_age_exceeded
Only present when
.B \-\-max\-age
is used. Boolean: true if
.B oldest_scrub_days
exceeds the threshold.
.SH "EXIT CODES"
.TP
.B 0
Normal exit. All checks passed.
.TP
.B 2
.B \-\-max\-age
was specified and the oldest scrub age exceeds the threshold.
.TP
.B 3
Configuration or runtime error (missing config file, content file not
found, terminal too narrow).
.SH CACHE
.TP
.I /var/cache/snapstats/snapstats.cache
Pickle file storing parsed file statistics. Keyed on the content file path,
mtime, and size. TTL: 2 hours. The directory is created automatically on
first run.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B NO_COLOR
If set to any non-empty value, disables ANSI color output.
Equivalent to
.BR \-\-no\-color .
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Default scrub age report:
.B snapstats
.TP
Full report with per-disk breakdown and 30 oldest files:
.B snapstats \-\-disk \-\-top 30
.TP
Alert if any file is older than 30 days (for cron):
.B snapstats \-q \-\-max\-age 30 || echo "scrub overdue"
.TP
Machine-readable output with threshold check:
.B snapstats \-\-json \-\-max\-age 21
.TP
Force re-parse ignoring cache:
.B snapstats \-\-no\-cache
.TP
Inspect a non-default content file:
.B snapstats \-\-content /mnt/tank/snapraid.content
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.BR snapraid (1)
.SH NOTES
snapstats does not verify data integrity. For scrub operations use
.BR "snapraid scrub" .
To scrub files with no scrub record:
.PP
.RS
.B snapraid scrub \-p 0 \-o 0
.RE
.SH AUTHOR
Written with Claude (Anthropic).
